stylometry:
Bayes theorem allows us to look at historical data and compare it to new possibilities that are conditional to the historical data to predict the new possibilities' occurence. So if we own a company that produces boats, and we have data on how well the last boat we produced was accepted by our market, we can look at the new boat we want to produce and predict the liklihood of our market will accept the new product as well.
So posterior probabilites are found by looking at the historical data, from that data we can predict new outcomes. Using them is important because if we have no prior data, just making a new product, throwing it at our market, and crossing our fingers for good luck will probably end up to be very catastrophic for our company if it goes badly. Using posterior probabilites, we can be more prepared for the potential outcomes of a new product.
